{"id":"1901.09577","submitter":"Jie Lu","authors":"Mei Li, Zhong An, and Jie Lu","title":"Ultra-high differential mobility and velocity of N\\'{e}el walls in spin\n  valves with planar-transverse polarizers under low perpendicularly injected\n  currents","comments":"11 pages, 6 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 100, 064406 (2019)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.100.064406","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Transverse domain wall (TDW) dynamics in long and narrow spin valves with\nperpendicular current injection is theoretically investigated. We demonstrate\nthat stable traveling-wave motion of TDWs with finite velocity survives for\nstrong enough planar-transverse polarizers. For typical ferromagnetic materials\n(for example, Co) and achievable spin polarization ($P=0.6$), TDWs acquire a\nvelocity of $10^3$ m/s under a current density below $10^7$ $\\mathrm{A/cm^2}$.\nThis efficiency is comparable with that of perpendicular polarizers. More\nimportantly, in this case the wall has ultra-high \"differential mobility\"\naround the onset of stable wall excitation. Our results open new possibilities\nfor developing magnetic nanodevices based on TDW propagation with low energy\nconsumption. Also, analytics for parallel and perpendicular polarizers\nperfectly explains existing simulation findings. Finally, further boosting of\nTDWs by external uniform transverse magnetic fields is investigated and turns\nout to be efficient.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 28 Jan 2019 09:45:21 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 22 Apr 2019 10:19:27 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 11 Jul 2019 05:10:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-08-14"}
